Feature: bc-container launch --startup-prompt commits the prompt to the in-container agent by issuing two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver — a text-only invocation followed by an Enter-only invocation

  Supersedes scenario 27 (features/bc-launcher/27-launch-with-startup-prompt-submits-prompt-autonomously.gherkin). The Implementer must locate the BC-side hash of scenario 27 in the shopsystem-bc-launcher feature surface and retire that hash when landing this scenario.

  Scenario 27 pinned the user-meaningful behavior ("the agent processes the prompt without further input") in terms of the agent's input-loop state, but that pin was satisfied by a single tmux send-keys invocation carrying both the prompt text and the Enter key as discrete argv elements — which is the empirically-buggy shape: tmux concatenates the multi-argv keystream into one pty write() syscall, and Claude Code's TUI heuristically absorbs the trailing CR into its input buffer (paste-mode-like behavior on single-write payloads above ~70 bytes) rather than treating it as a discrete submit keypress. The empirical fix (lead-9q0f Probes 3 and 5, plus the live launcher end-to-end re-test on bc-shopsystem-docs) is to issue the text and the Enter as two separate send-keys invocations, which produces two discrete pty write() syscalls separated by a kernel-scheduling gap that the TUI processes as a discrete keypress event.

  This scenario re-grounds the launch-path pin from "the prompt is committed" (which the single-invocation shape spuriously satisfies in the testing layer) to "the BC issues two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver, in order: a text-only invocation carrying the prompt text and no Enter token, followed by an Enter-only invocation carrying the Enter token and no prompt text". The driver-surface assertion turns red under any single-invocation shape (whether the buggy "text and Enter in one argv" shape, or any variant carrying both payloads in one invocation), so any future regression to a single-write submission attempt is caught at the BC's contract surface without requiring a live TUI.

  Scenario: bc-container launch --startup-prompt issues two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver — first the prompt text alone, then the Enter key alone — and no single invocation carries both
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    When I run "bc-container launch shopsystem-messaging --startup-prompt 'bd prime'" and the launch command exits zero
    Then the BC has issued exactly two tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver targeting the tmux session named "agent" in container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" as a direct consequence of the --startup-prompt being honored
    And the first of those two invocations carries the prompt text "bd prime" as its key payload and does not carry the Enter key in the same invocation
    And the second of those two invocations carries the Enter key as its key payload and does not carry the prompt text "bd prime" in the same invocation
    And no single tmux send-keys invocation issued by the launch command's --startup-prompt handling carries both the prompt text "bd prime" and the Enter key together
    And the two invocations are issued in order: the text-only invocation first, the Enter-only invocation second
